<Link id="l00680" /><CodeLine lineNumber="680"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00681" /><CodeLine lineNumber="681"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Merge 2 debug locations and apply it to the Instruction. If the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00682" /><CodeLine lineNumber="682"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// instruction is a CallIns, we need to traverse the inline chain to find</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00683" /><CodeLine lineNumber="683"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the common scope. This is not efficient for N-way merging as each time</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00684" /><CodeLine lineNumber="684"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// you merge 2 iterations, you need to rebuild the hashmap to find the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00685" /><CodeLine lineNumber="685"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// common scope. However, we still choose this API because:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00686" /><CodeLine lineNumber="686"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///  1) Simplicity: it takes 2 locations instead of a list of locations.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00687" /><CodeLine lineNumber="687"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///  2) In worst case, it increases the complexity from O(N&#42;I) to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00688" /><CodeLine lineNumber="688"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     O(2&#42;N&#42;I), where N is # of Instructions to merge, and I is the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00689" /><CodeLine lineNumber="689"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     maximum level of inline stack. So it is still linear.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00690" /><CodeLine lineNumber="690"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///  3) Merging of call instructions should be extremely rare in real</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00691" /><CodeLine lineNumber="691"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     applications, thus the N-way merging should be in code path.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00692" /><CodeLine lineNumber="692"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The DebugLoc attached to this instruction will be overwritten by the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00693" /><CodeLine lineNumber="693"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// merged DebugLoc.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00694" /><CodeLine lineNumber="694"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">void</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> applyMergedLocation(DILocation &#42;LocA, DILocation &#42;LocB);</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00695" /><CodeLine lineNumber="695"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00696" /><CodeLine lineNumber="696"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Updates the debug location given that the instruction has been hoisted</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00698" /><CodeLine lineNumber="698"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Note: it is undefined behavior to call this on an instruction not</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00699" /><CodeLine lineNumber="699"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// currently inserted into a function.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00700" /><CodeLine lineNumber="700"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">void</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> updateLocationAfterHoist();</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00701" /><CodeLine lineNumber="701"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00702" /><CodeLine lineNumber="702"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Drop the instruction&#39;s debug location. This does not guarantee removal</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00703" /><CodeLine lineNumber="703"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// of the !dbg source location attachment, as it must set a line 0 location</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00704" /><CodeLine lineNumber="704"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// with scope information attached on call instructions. To guarantee</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00705" /><CodeLine lineNumber="705"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// removal of the !dbg attachment, use the \\ref setDebugLoc() API.</span></CodeLine>
